---
description: Blank lines inside functions — returns, control flow, const/let blocks
alwaysApply: true
---

# Function Spacing

Use blank lines to separate logical steps inside a function. Do not pack unrelated statements together.

## Returns

Always put a blank line immediately before every `return` (including early returns).

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
if (!user) {
  return null;
}

const profile = await loadProfile(user);

return profile;

// ❌ BAD
if (!user) {
  return null;
}
const profile = await loadProfile(user);
return profile;
```

## Control flow

Put a blank line **before and after** `if`, `else`, `for`, `while`, `do`, `switch`, and `try` / `catch` / `finally` blocks when they sit among other statements.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const rows = await fetchRows();

for (const row of rows) {
  await processRow(row);
}

switch (row.kind) {
  case "a":
    handleA(row);
    break;
  default:
    handleDefault(row);
}

return { count: rows.length };

// ❌ BAD — no breathing room around control flow
const rows = await fetchRows();
for (const row of rows) {
  await processRow(row);
}
switch (row.kind) {
  case "a": handleA(row); break;
}
return { count: rows.length };
```

Inside long `if` / loop bodies, separate distinct steps with blank lines the same way.

## Variable groups

Group declarations by kind. Keep **`const`** declarations together, then a blank line, then **`let`** declarations together. Do not interleave `const` and `let`.

**Always** put a blank line after the last declaration in a `const` or `let` block before any following statement (calls, control flow, `return`, etc.).

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const profile = await loadProfile(user);

processProfile(profile);

// ❌ BAD
const profile = await loadProfile(user);
processProfile(profile);
```

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const accountId = options.accountId;
const client = createClient(config);

let collected = 0;
let failures: string[] = [];

for (const item of items) {
  /* ... */
}

// ❌ BAD
const accountId = options.accountId;
let collected = 0;
const client = createClient(config);
let failures: string[] = [];
for (const item of items) {
  /* ... */
}
```

Multiple `const` or multiple `let` in the same group need no blank line between each other unless a subgroup is a distinct logical step.

## Logical sections

Separate setup, mutation/work, and teardown/result with blank lines when a function has more than one phase.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
export async function runJob(options: JobOptions): Promise<JobResult> {
  const config = resolveConfig(options);
  const client = buildClient(config);

  let processed = 0;

  for (const item of options.items) {
    await client.process(item);
    processed += 1;
  }

  await client.close();

  return { processed };
}
```

When editing existing functions, apply these spacing rules to the changed region and match surrounding style where it already follows this rule.
